PART 7 : EXPERIMENTS
Experiment 1: Baseline OCSVM with All Features
Goal: Establish initial performance using the full feature set (~441 features) and default hyperparameters.

Procedure:

Ran train_session.py with drop_cols containing only metadata columns (all sensor features used).

Used nu=0.05, gamma=0.00055, threshold=0.

Evaluated on all 17 users (global average).

Results:

Accuracy: ~69%

TAR: ~68%

FAR: ~0.15% (very low)

FRR: ~32%

Observations:

Model is too strict – many genuine sessions rejected (high FRR).

FAR is excellent; the boundary is extremely tight around training data.

Indicates overfitting or inadequate hyperparameters.

Lesson: Default OCSVM settings do not generalise well with this feature dimensionality.

Experiment 2: Manual Feature Selection via drop_cols
Goal: Find a feature subset that improves TAR by trial-and-error.

Procedure:

The team manually commented/uncommented features in the drop_cols list.

For each combination, ran the full training script and noted global TAR.

Two subsets were found that individually improved TAR (e.g., subset A gave +2%, subset B gave +3%).

When both subsets were combined, TAR decreased.

Results:

Individual gains disappeared when merging.

Combined set performed worse than either alone.

Observations:

Hyperparameters were never re‑tuned for the new feature sets.

The “combination pitfall” is due to fixed nu, gamma, threshold that were optimal for the old set.

Lesson: Feature selection without hyperparameter re‑tuning is unreliable. Automatic tuning is required.

Experiment 3: Per‑Axis FFT Features
Goal: Add individual axis FFT features (previously only magnitude) and measure accuracy change.

Procedure:

Modified extract_fft_features to call _extract_windowed_fft for acc_x, acc_y, acc_z, gyro_x, gyro_y, gyro_z.

Regenerated CSVs, ran manual evaluation with fixed hyperparameters.

Results:

No immediate TAR gain; accuracy stayed the same or slightly decreased for some users.

Scatter plots showed better separation of genuine and impostor scores, but TAR didn’t reflect it.

Observations:

The model couldn’t exploit the new features because hyperparameters were still tuned for the old feature set.

Hyperparameter tuning needed to unlock the benefit.

Lesson: New features must be accompanied by a fresh hyperparameter search.

Experiment 4: MFCC and Multitaper Spectral Features
Goal: Integrate advanced frequency‑domain features (MFCC and multitaper) and evaluate.

Procedure:

Added methods _extract_mfcc_features and _extract_multitaper_features to the feature extractor.

Initially, these methods were defined but not called inside extract_fft_features – a critical oversight.

After discovering this, the extract_fft_features method was updated to call both for magnitude and each axis.

CSVs were regenerated, training script rerun with fixed hyperparameters.

Results:

Before fixing the missing calls: no change in TAR (features weren’t present).

After the fix and retraining with nu=0.2, gamma=0.00055, threshold=-0.3: TAR improved (exact amount not quantified in logs, but positive).

The earlier lack of gain was due to the features not being generated.

Observations:

Integration mistakes can completely nullify new features.

Once properly included, the extra features provided additional discriminative power.

Lesson: Always verify the generated CSV columns after modifying the extractor.

Experiment 5: Global Hyperparameter Tuning (Naive)
Goal: Quickly find best nu, gamma, threshold using the same 3‑user dataset.

Procedure:

Used tune_global.py – trains each user on their own genuine data, tests on their own test data, and averages TAR over all users.

Grid: nu in [0.01,0.02,0.05,0.1,0.2,0.3], threshold in [-0.3,-0.2,-0.1,0,0.1,0.2], gamma candidates from fixed 0.00055 and adaptive multipliers.

Selected combination with highest average TAR while FAR ≤ 0.5%.

Results:

Best parameters: nu=0.2, gamma=0.00055, threshold=-0.3.

Reported global TAR much higher than baseline (exact value not preserved, but significantly improved).

However, applying these parameters back to the main script caused accuracy to drop.

Observations:

The global method tunes directly on the test set, causing overfitting.

The parameters looked great on the 3 users used for tuning but failed to generalise.

The feature count mismatch (101 vs 85) between training and tuning scripts also contributed.

Lesson: Global averaging on the same test set used for selection yields optimistically biased hyperparameters. A cross‑validation approach is mandatory.

Experiment 6: Leave‑One‑User‑Out (LOUO) Hyperparameter Tuning
Goal: Obtain honest, generalisable hyperparameters via cross‑validation.

Procedure:

Developed tune_louo.py (later extended to tune_louo_expanded.py).

For each fold, trained OCSVM on genuine data of all users except one, tested on the held‑out user.

Evaluated average TAR, FRR, FAR across folds.

Grid expanded to 12 nu values, 10 threshold values, and 11 gamma values (fixed 0.00055 + 10 adaptive multipliers).

Constraints: FAR ≤ 0.5%, FRR ≤ 30%.

Initially run on 3 users; later adapted for 10 users.

Results:

On the 3‑user set, the LOUO search gave nu=0.2, gamma=0.00055, threshold=-0.3 (coincidentally matching the global best for that small set, but validated honestly).

On 10 users (pending execution), the script is ready and expected to produce a more robust parameter set.

The LOUO average TAR is lower than the global tuning TAR, but it reflects true generalisation.

Observations:

With only 3 users, the LOUO estimate is noisy but still more trustworthy than global tuning.

The script includes a wide range of nu values (up to 0.5) and gamma (down to 0.01×), ensuring coverage.

Lesson: LOUO is the correct tuning strategy for per‑user models.

Experiment 7: Hardcoded Threshold Fix
Goal: Understand why TAR didn’t change after hyperparameter tuning.

Procedure:

Discovered that the evaluate() method in train_session.py used a hardcoded threshold 0 regardless of the tuned value.

Corrected it to use the variable threshold (set to -0.3).

Results:

Immediately after fixing, TAR increased noticeably (exact values not recorded but clear improvement).

The previous tuning runs were partially void because the threshold was never actually changed.

Observations:

A single hardcoded constant can undermine an entire tuning effort.

All hyperparameters must be parameterised in the evaluation code.

Lesson: Always verify that tuned parameters are actually injected into the model.

Experiment 8: Feature Ranking via Boruta + SHAP (Phase 2A)
Goal: Identify all‑relevant features using Boruta and rank them with SHAP importance.

Procedure:

Used 13 development users, cleaned feature set from Phase 1.

Boruta (XGBoost, multi:softprob, 100 iterations) → kept Selected + Tentative features.

SHAP TreeExplainer → mean absolute SHAP across all classes.

Output: boruta_shap_ranking.csv with boruta_status column.

Results:

Boruta retained ~100‑200 features (Selected + Tentative).

SHAP ranking provided a smooth ordering.

Visual inspection showed top features were intuitive (HMOG, FFT, touch).

Observations:

Boruta removed truly noisy features, but kept many tentatives.

SHAP importance aligned with domain knowledge.

Lesson: Boruta + SHAP is a reliable wrapper‑based ranking method.

Experiment 9: Feature Ranking via Fisher Score (Phase 2B)
Goal: Rank features by their ability to separate users (between‑ vs within‑class variance).

Procedure:

Fisher score = between‑user variance / within‑user variance.

Computed on 13 dev users’ genuine training data, after Phase 1 cleaning.

Results:

Produced fisher_ranking.csv.

Top features included many touch and HMOG features.

Visualization (box plots, heatmaps) confirmed strong user separation.

Observations:

Fisher score is purely linear and doesn’t capture interactions.

It gave a different ranking than Boruta, highlighting complementary perspectives.

Lesson: Multiple independent rankings are essential.

Experiment 10: Feature Ranking via RF Leave‑One‑User‑Out (Phase 2C)
Goal: Rank features using Random Forest trained on genuine vs. impostor data from other users.

Procedure:

For each target user, built a training set from all other users (genuine + impostor).

RF with n_estimators=300, class_weight='balanced'.

Averaged feature importances across folds.

Results:

rf_louo_importance.csv produced a ranking that often differed from Boruta and Fisher.

This ranking directly measures discriminative power for fraud detection.

Observations:

Using impostor data makes this ranking highly relevant to the final task.

The LOUO scheme ensures no data leakage.

Lesson: RF LOUO is a strong embedded feature selector for this problem.

Experiment 11: Consensus Ranking (Phase 3)
Goal: Merge the three rankings into a single robust list.

Procedure:

Converted each ranking’s scores to percentiles.

Weighted average: 50% Boruta‑SHAP, 35% RF, 15% Fisher.

Missing features (not present in all three) filled with 0.5.

Stability score = standard deviation of percentiles.

Results:

consensus_ranking.csv provides a final ordered list with trustworthiness indicators.

Features with high average percentile and low std are the most reliable.

Observations:

The weighting reflects the relative importance of each method for the authentication task.

The stability score helps identify features that are universally top‑ranked.

Lesson: Weighted consensus with missing‑value neutrality is a powerful aggregation.

Experiment 12: K‑Selection with Fixed Hyperparameters (Phase 5)
Goal: Find the optimal number of consensus features using default OCSVM settings.

Procedure:

For K from 10 to 150, used top‑K consensus features.

Trained OCSVM with nu=0.1, gamma=1/K, threshold=0.

Evaluated via LOUO on 13 dev users; selected K with minimum HTER.

Results:

K=10 gave the best HTER, but accuracy ~70%, far below the lead’s 75% TAR with ~100 features.

Larger K values performed worse under these default hyperparameters.

Observations:

The fixed hyperparameters penalise larger feature sets because gamma becomes too small.

This experiment does not reflect the true potential of larger feature sets after tuning.

Lesson: K‑selection with fixed hyperparameters is misleading; the full grid search is needed.

Experiment 13: Lead’s Hand‑Picked Feature Set
Goal: Evaluate the team lead’s manually curated set of ~97‑103 features.

Procedure:

The lead had previously identified a combination that gave TAR ~75% after some tuning.

The exact hyperparameters used by the lead are not fully documented, but the set was tested within the team’s workflow.

Not all features from the consensus top‑10 were included (some highly ranked features were excluded, and inclusion decreased TAR).

Results:

TAR ~75% on the test set.

Attempts to add the top consensus feature (ranked #1 by Boruta and Fisher, #6 by RF) caused TAR to drop below 70% when combined with the lead’s set without re‑tuning.

Observations:

Interaction between features and hyperparameters is critical.

The lead’s set likely already has a tuned configuration that doesn’t accommodate new features without parameter adjustment.

Lesson: The final feature set must be chosen via a fair comparison of candidate sets with full hyperparameter tuning.

Experiment 14: Overfitting Check via Validation Split
Goal: Detect overfitting in per‑user models.

Procedure:

Added validate() method to SessionOCSVM (not yet integrated into main).

Splits genuine training data 80/20, trains temporary OCSVM, measures FRR on validation.

Results:

Not yet executed systematically.

Designed to issue a warning if validation FRR > 0.15.

Observations:

This is a diagnostic tool, not a tuning method.

High validation FRR would suggest increasing nu or reducing features.

Lesson: Simple hold‑out validation can catch overfitting early.

Summary of Key Learnings
Hyperparameters must be tuned for each feature set.

LOUO cross‑validation is the only honest way to select hyperparameters.

Combining good feature subsets without re‑tuning often degrades performance.

Always verify that tuned parameters are actually used in the final script.

Multiple ranking methods provide complementary views; consensus is more robust than any single method.

Feature‑selection K‑value cannot be judged with default hyperparameters.

